      <hedline>
        <hl1>Tales From Aloft</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Kay Gardner Bergl letter on June 25 travel article recalls sleeping in Pullmanlike berth aboard airliner in 1956; photo (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor: The article ''Bedding Down at 35,000 Feet'' (June 25) brought back memories of a flight in 1956 on the Monarch Service of B.O.A.C. (now British Airways), for which I worked at the time.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor: The article ''Bedding Down at 35,000 Feet'' (June 25) brought back memories of a flight in 1956 on the Monarch Service of B.O.A.C. (now British Airways), for which I worked at the time.</p>
        <p>I was pregnant and flying home to England to see my parents. The flying time -- if I remember rightly -- was something like 12 hours, with a stopover in Gander, Newfoundland, or Iceland (or perhaps both?). About an hour out of New York I felt ill, but was very kindly taken by the air hostess (as a stewardess was called then) to a berth, somewhat similar to the one in the photo. Fortunately I survived the rest of the flight and my baby was not born on board!</p>
        <p>KAY GARDNER BERGL  Roslyn Heights, N.Y.</p>
      </block>
